<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from  The UK Data Service [DOD08]</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from  T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he UK Data Service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">OD08</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">]</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n ESRC-funded data service infrastructure. It is based on collaboration between the UK Data Archive (University of Essex), the Cathie Marsh Centre for Census and Survey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mimas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (both University of Manchester) and the Department of Geography at the University of Southampton. The UK Data Service and its predecessors have been providing access to data to higher education since 1967. In more recent years the remit of the service has been to widen participation and provide possibilities for broadening the use of data which had traditionally been restricted to higher education and government departments and related bodies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Data Service believes firmly that appropriate mechanisms are required to make data accessible without any risk of disclosure. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We fully support the “Open Data Agenda” in as much as it has the potential to make more government data available; and it has already allowed us to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">open up access and usage to data by many individuals and organ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">izations (e.g. third sector and other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">individuals) who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">been adequately served by any previous service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(funded by the ESRC) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and whom we have repeatedly had to turn away</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, we believe that the Agenda may also have some unforeseen effects which are deleterious to the existing data-using communities in both the public and third sectors. We focus on these potentially negative elements below, while acknowledging great positive steps.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">response </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is submitted by the UK Data Service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It has been prepared by Matthew </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Woollard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Director, UK Data Service. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It does not necessarily reflect the views of the Economic and Social Research Council (ESR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C) or the Universities of Essex, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or Southampton</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. For further details please contact Matthew </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Woollard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><a href="mailto:matthew@essex.ac.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">matthew@essex.ac.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1. Why is open data important?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All data generated by government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> important. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They allow government to function. They</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> allow governmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t to be accountable to citizens.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They provide value to researchers through their re-use. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Providing public access, for whatever purpose, to some government data, has clear economic and social benefits, and provides additional return on investment. For example, the return on investment of government-sponsored surveys, e.g., Labour Force Survey, Census, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etc., </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is greater and continues longer by making the underlying data available</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, to all users</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Similarly routinely collected statistics when published have impact beyond their original purpose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncreasingly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">microdata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from the administrative processes of government are providing value which “offset” their costs of collection and maintenance.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, open data is neither the beginning nor the end of the issue. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Open Data Agenda </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seems to be driving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">towards the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">removal of all access restrictions from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">subset of data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">created by government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rather than reviewing and revising access restrictions across the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whole portfolio.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> If the open data agenda has the effect of making it harder to access some data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">then the overall benefits of the agenda are reduced.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> There will, because of legal constraints, always be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should only be used for particular purposes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or by particular </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">communities of user</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (e.g., Approved Researchers). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2. Why does the Government need an open data strategy?</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is required </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to take into account different access mechanisms which best promote the reuse of data. The existing strategy takes little account of other mechanisms which are available, like the ESRC’s UK Data Service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><a href="http://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">www.ukdataservice.ac.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) which provides access to government-funded research data (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> data created as a by-product of academic social and economic research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> data which has potential reuse value for social and economic research.) The UK Data Service also provides access to data at several levels of disclosure risk. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to deal with some of the other more complex requirements about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roviding access to data. For example the White Paper does not include reference to the length of time data will be publicly available, or to the archival/curatorial aspects of open data. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is required to ensure that the best </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use is made of the data which are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provided. Reasonable and pragmatic solutions need to be devised to ensure both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the released data are as fine-grained as possible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rights of persons or businesses who may be included within the data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are guaranteed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> National Pupil Database is a great example of data which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not (using the White Paper’s definition) ‘Open’ but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being made available for particular research purposes. We believe that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has taken the right approach here, and not made these data ‘Open’, but have increased the potential for access while protecting the data subjects. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to ensure that there is a unified approach in establishing different risks of disclosure associated with different types of data and how to handle their dissemination (via OGL, other forms of licensing, approved researcher status, etc.) across government departments and national statistical agencies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is required to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the quality of the data which are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provided is as high as is possible (see below). There is a general sense among academic researchers that the integrity, provenance and quali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ty of data which has been made </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">open is often ignored. It is very important to recognise that many government-produced datasets which are open, especially those relating to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensus, are exactly the same definitive products as before. There is no suggestion that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> quality has altered in any way, only that access has become universal, and the purposes to which the data can be put has been immensely improved.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3. What should the Government’s aims be for the release of open data?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a. Are the Government’s stated key outcomes in its Open Data Strategy the right ones?</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It’s not actually clear that “the Government” has an Open Data Strategy. Most government departments seem to have published a strategy which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focusses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the transparency aspects of releasing data. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We cannot find an example of where a department explicitly treats ‘Open Data’ as part of a con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tinuum of access levels. Characterising data as a binary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ‘Open or Not’ is not accurate and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ignore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">possibility of much greater </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">value </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and impact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of more limited access criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It also leads to a risk that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government departments will simply evaluate data as ‘Should not be Open’ on a precautionary principle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4. How can those engaged in open data, and those engaged in producing government statistics work together effectively to produce new data?</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Producers and users of data do need to work together, but this goes far beyond those engaged in open data and those engaged in producing statistics. There are many thousands of researchers, within commerce and academia who are daily trying to gain easy access to data produced in government, but whose ambitions are thwarted by government departments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and national statistical agencies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. One example, the UK Data Service has regularly received (from 1985) Road Accident Data from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which are published under an End User Licence (not OGL).</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The most recent series released to the UK Data Service covers 2010, but less detailed versions of these data are available via data.gov.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Serious researchers are currently unable to carry out comparative analyses of these data. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5. How can more statistics and administrative data of all kinds become more freely available?</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Data Service believes that more data can be made available through a number of mechanisms. The first step, whereby each government department has published an Open Data Strategy is already implemented. The second step would be to enlarge this to publish Data Strategies which included other forms of licensing/access mechanisms to establish a more holistic approach to the publication of data. This strategy must be based on a clear “catalogue” of all data which are either produced or captured by each department. Key data users from all stakeholder groups could then provide a programme of publication whereby datasets could be made available in different versions to different user communities. A fine example will be the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">microdata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from the 2011 census, where an Open version will be available to download from the ONS website (and potentially elsewhere), a ‘controlled access version’ which would not be able to be redistributed and would contain additional protections to deal with any limited risk of disclosure and a ‘secure access’ version which will only be available in safe settings by researchers who have met the criteria for Approved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Researchers. Only by taking an overall approach to individual data collections will the resulting use of data produced by government be maximised. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here exist many different needs for data, by different user groups, ranging from aggregate data to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">microdata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These different groups often have different requirements in terms of detailed geographies or different levels of information about individuals, but these cannot often be provided because of the likely levels of disclosure possible through linkage. New access mechanisms need to be put into place that reduces the risk of disclosure, while maximising the potential of the data. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is clear evidence that the greater the barriers to accessing data, the fewer researchers are willing to use it. Greater barriers are perceived by data owners to provide greater protection to the data subjects, thus one can imagine decisions about access being made on the basis that “my data is more personal than theirs, so I must need more information security”. This ‘classification creep’ may be being stoked by the Open Data Agenda where the blunt tool of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anonymisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is being used to reduce the opportunities of access to high detail information. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6. Is open data presented well and of adequate quality?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a. Are the formats of the data being published accessible, useable and understandable to the public?</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In general</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> yes, but there are countless examples of (avoidable) errors. One random example: recently the Treasury Department published the Bona </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Vacantia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Unclaimed Estates and Adverts.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The CSV file was created by someone whose knowledge of the way in which MS Excel handles dates is poor, consequently the date of birth of at least 132 people (more than 1% of the total) is reported as being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">after</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their date of death. (And the marital status of some suggests that other ages are wrong too – for example, there is a two month old widow!) The lack of quality control mechanisms mean that this data collection is riddled with errors. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, while data.gov.uk does provide some form of “change” log, it doesn’t tell you what </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changes have been made to the data file</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, or provide the “historical” version. Thus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">file which was available on 19</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">August is no longer available.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is not troubling for these data, but certain forecasts and projections of economic data cited in the Treasury Red Book have clearly been updated since they were used for the 2013 budget making it impossible to validate the original assumptions. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is also worth noting that usability of any distributed data cannot be judged solely on its format. Comma Separated Values may be of value for a small table of aggregate statistics, but it generally not helpful for survey data.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">b. What metadata is needed to make releases useful?</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Metadata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are required for various purposes, including, f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inding the material</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sing the material</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aintaining the material</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The first and last are specialist cases, but must not be ignored. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK Data Service usually suggest that the level of metadata </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provided to support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> use (aka documentation) should allow the material to be independently understandable by the target audience, i.e., they do not need to refer to the data creator to understand them. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Essentially this level of metadata is required at the variable level (a code used has this value) and at the dataset level (these data were created by this method, for this purpose and by this organisation, etc.) </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We randomly chose ten recently uploaded spread sheets from data.gov.uk. In every case we found column and row headings which were undefined within the data file provided or on the data.gov.uk site. In most (but not all) cases these could be “decoded” with recourse to Wikipedia. But, for the naïve user these data are not independently understandable. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One example: DCLG publish indices of multiple deprivation via the data.gov.uk site, which are extraordinary useful for social and economic research, but in the files published</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> only standard codes for LA can be easily mapped to local authority names; the accompanying notes provide no equivalent reference point for the LSOAs (Lower Layer Super Output Areas).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">c. Who will use the data released?</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Data Service’s user community is predominantly made up of researchers and students in higher education, the third sector, NGOs, government (local and national) and commercial organisations including journalists, and the general public. This will comprise a key element of the community for the open data initiative, but the user community will be wider and should attract more of the public and more commercial exploitation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7. How successful has the Government’s Open Data initiative been in changing behaviour in the Civil Service and wider public sector?</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In general, we feel that it has been positive, but there is a long way to go.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8. Which datasets are the most important?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a. What are the best examples of data being made open and resultant benefits to business or society?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">9. How effective is the work being undertaken by the Cabinet Office to monitor the progress of Departments in publishing their agreed datasets?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://discover.ukdataservice.ac.uk/series/?sn=2000045"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://discover.ukdataservice.ac.uk/series/?sn=2000045</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> [Available 30 August 2013]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.data.gov.uk/dataset/road-accidents-safety-data"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.data.gov.uk/dataset/road-accidents-safety-data</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> [Available 30 August 2013]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.bonavacantia.gov.uk/upload/EstatesList-2013-08-27.csv"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bonavacantia.gov.uk/upload/EstatesList-2013-08-27.csv</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> [Available 30 August 2013]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.bonavacantia.gov.uk/upload/EstatesList-2013-08-19.csv"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bonavacantia.gov.uk/upload/EstatesList-2013-08-19.csv</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> [Not available on 30 August 2013}</span></p></body></html>